The probabilities of interest:
P(x_conformsTo_i | pop_conformsTo_i) -> determines an individual action
P(pop_conformsTo_i | x_conformsTo_i) -> determines perception of norms

let P(x_conformsTo_i) = f(x,i) * P(pop_conformsTo_i) + f(x,i) * P(~pop_conformsTo_i)

where f(x,i) is a function for character x and norm i, based on individual preferences

let P(pop_conformsTo_i) = P(empiricalExpectation_i) 
							* ( P(normativeExpectation_i) + P(sanctionExpectation_i) )

ie: the expectations of a norm being performed, preference, and sanctioned
so... the averages of someone performing an action that expresses a norm, 
expressing a preference for a norm, and sanctioning an action that expresses a norm?


so:

P(pop_conformsTo_i | x_conformsTo_i) = P(x_conformsTo_i | pop_conformsTo_i) * P(pop_conformsTo_i)
													/ P(x_conformsTo_i)

and:

P(x_conformsTo_i | pop_conformsTo_i) = P(pop_conformsTo_i | x_conformsTo_i) * P(x_conformsTo_i)
													/ P(pop_conformsTo_i)



